Rating: 3
To keep the torte from sticking to the pan; butter the bottom of the pan, cut a round of parchment, place it in the pan, butter the parchment and the sides then flour the whole pan. It is now ready for the batter. Do not over cook this torte, if your oven temperature is correct 40 minutes is plenty of cooking time.

Rating: 3
I expected a little more out of this recipe because of all the positive reviews. It was good, but to be honest it was little more than a decadent brownie (not a fudge-like brownie but like a crumbly brownie because of the ground almonds.) There was nothing wrong with the way it tasted and people liked it, but it's a lot easier to make a brownie. Anyway, I have to stress that the torte really sticks to the pan. I knew it was an issue so I buttered the pan well but that wasn't good enough. I know Williams-Sonoma makes an expensive spray-on product that is supposedly stellar at preventing this. Maybe that's the thing to use. Also, instead of making 1 big torte I used small springform pans instead. I used 3 pans because I knew this dessert was dense and I didn't think it would rise that much. I was wrong. Next time I will probably use 4 pans. 3 pans will give you that muffin top effect (unattractive with this dessert), and it makes it difficult to get the dessert out.

